de.arraytools.java

Class ArrayToolsInt

  • java.lang.Object
    • de.arraytools.java.ArrayToolsInt

  • public class ArrayToolsInt
extends java.lang.Object

    Tools for int Arrays!

    This library makes the use of arrays easier. The methods are simple but frequently used with arrays.

    Note: The methods, where one of the parameters is a Comparator, Consumer or Function can be a bit complicated at first but take a look at the README.txt file to understand the usage of these methods!
    Since:
    2019-05-09
    Version:
    1.1
    Author:
    Niklas Koll, Felix Brosius

      • forEach

        public static void forEach(int[] array,
                           java.util.function.Consumer<java.lang.Integer> function)
        Uses the specified function on every element in the array. For example: forEach(numArray, num -> System.out.print(num + " ")); to print out all the elements.

        The parameter of the function is an element of the array. It iterates over every element and uses it as the parameter.

        Important: Only functions, that don't change the element's value work. If you want to apply changes to each element use applyForEach(int[], Function).

        Note: For the easiest and best usage, use lambda expressions for the function.
        Parameters:
        array - the array to go through
        function - function that is being used on every element Note: has to be void
        Since:
        1.0

      • applyForEach

        public static void applyForEach(int[] array,
                                java.util.function.Function<java.lang.Integer,java.lang.Integer> function)
        Uses the specified function on every element in the array. For example: applyForEach(numArray, num -> num*2) to multiply all elements by 2.

        The parameter of the function is an element of the array. It iterates over every element and uses it as the parameter. The function returns a new Value of the given type, to which the element in the array is function to.

        Important: Only functions, that change the element's value work. If you don't want to apply changes to each element use forEach(int[], Consumer).

        Note: For the easiest and best usage, use lambda expressions for the methods.
        Parameters:
        array - the array to go through
        function - function that is being used on every element Note: has to return an int. Note: The only parameter the function can have is the current element
        Since:
        1.0
